  'The KNBC Broadcast Interruption — Seven Minutes the Public Was Never Allowed to See',
  'On August 19, 1987, Gary Stollman interrupted a live KNBC broadcast, forcing anchor David Horowitz to read a statement at gunpoint for seven minutes. The station cut the feed after 28 seconds, but continued recording. The full footage has never been publicly released.',
  E'THE EVENT\n\nOn August 19, 1987, at 4:42 p.m. during KNBC''s Channel 4 News at 4 in Los Angeles, a 34-year-old man named Gary Stollman walked up behind veteran consumer reporter David Horowitz during a live broadcast, pressed what appeared to be a .45-caliber handgun into his back, and said: "Read this or I''ll shoot you." Horowitz — believing the weapon was real — put on his spectacles and began reading aloud from several pages of handwritten yellow legal paper. KNBC News Director Tom Capra ordered the broadcast cut to black 28 seconds later. Viewers saw an NBC logo with a "technical difficulties" voiceover. But the cameras never stopped rolling. For the next seven minutes, Horowitz continued reading the full statement at gunpoint while Stollman — unaware the feed had been cut — repeatedly asked: "Am I on the air? Am I?" When Horowitz finished reading the final line, Stollman placed the weapon on the desk and said: "Thank you, David. I couldn''t have harmed anyone with this unloaded BB gun." Co-anchor John Beard grabbed the weapon. Burbank police, who had entered the studio during the reading, swarmed in and arrested Stollman. The gun was a plastic toy — a children''s replica of a .45-caliber pistol with a spring mechanism that fired small plastic pellets capable of traveling roughly 10 feet. Burbank Police Sergeant Joe Latta told the Los Angeles Times: "You can''t call it a pellet gun, even. It''s just for children."\n\nTHE STATEMENT\n\nThe first paragraph of Stollman''s handwritten statement read: "The man who has appeared on KNBC for the past three years is not my biological father. He is a clone, a double created by the Central Intelligence Agency and alien forces. It is only a small part of a greater plot to overthrow the United States government, and possibly the human race itself." The statement went on to allege mistreatment in what Stollman described as "CIA-run mental hospitals" and demanded the release of "secret Air Force files concerning UFOs." Horowitz later told reporters: "The first paragraph was enough to tell me this guy was a lunatic." He frequently had difficulty deciphering the handwriting.\n\nHOW STOLLMAN GAINED ACCESS\n\nGary Stollman was not a random intruder. His father, Max Stollman, was a pharmacist who had worked as an on-air pharmaceutical reporter for KNBC throughout the 1970s and early 1980s. Gary exploited this connection to gain studio access. Days before the incident, he telephoned co-anchor Kirstie Wilde, identified himself as Max Stollman''s son, said he lived on the East Coast and had never seen his father''s former workplace, and asked to visit the studio. Wilde later told the Los Angeles Times: "He seemed a little unstable, or maybe not very bright." She agreed to let him visit. On August 19, Stollman called again and received authorization from News Director Tom Capra to enter the studio as a guest. He was given a pass, sat in a chair at the back of the studio, and no one noticed anything unusual until he approached Horowitz during the live broadcast.\n\nTHE STATION''S RESPONSE\n\nTom Capra ordered the live feed killed 28 seconds after Stollman appeared on camera. The station broadcast an NBC logo with promos for approximately seven minutes while Horowitz continued reading the full statement off-air. When the broadcast resumed, co-anchors John Beard and Kirstie Wilde explained what had happened. KNBC led its 5, 6, and 11 p.m. newscasts with the story. The station held a press conference at 6:30 p.m. for other media. Los Angeles Times television critic Howard Rosenberg wrote the following day: "In effect, Stollman did indeed take KNBC hostage, and the other media as well, by becoming a news story they could not ignore." Capra told reporters: "We took him off the air, because we cannot allow people like this to take television stations hostage."\n\nTHE AFTERMATH\n\nStollman was booked by Burbank Police on suspicion of threatening a crime with the intent of sowing terror and disrupting public activities — a felony. He was held at the Los Angeles County Jail without bail. In September 1987, Municipal Judge Alan Kalkin ordered him to stand trial on two felony charges: false imprisonment by use of violence and commercial burglary (on the theory that he entered KNBC studios with the intent to commit a felony and, in effect, stole air time from the station). His father, Max Stollman, issued a statement: "I do have a sick son. He has been hospitalized a number of times. I''m thankful he wasn''t killed."\n\nIn October 1987, the Mental Health Department of the Los Angeles Superior Court determined that Stollman was "gravely disabled as a result of a mental disorder" and appointed his mother as his conservator.\n\nOn June 7, 1988, Stollman accepted a plea deal. He pleaded guilty to misdemeanor false imprisonment. The two felony counts were dismissed. Pasadena Superior Court Judge Jack B. Tso placed him on three years'' probation with the condition that he continue receiving psychiatric treatment. Three psychiatrists wrote letters to the court stating that Stollman was not a danger to society as long as he received care. He was living at an undisclosed mental facility in the San Fernando Valley.\n\nTHE UNRELEASED FOOTAGE\n\nThe full seven-minute recording of Horowitz reading Stollman''s complete statement exists. KNBC continued recording after cutting the live broadcast. According to the Lost Media Wiki, the footage is classified as "partially found" — some clips appeared in subsequent news coverage of the incident, but the complete uninterrupted recording of Horowitz reading the full statement at gunpoint has never been publicly released. It remains in NBC''s archives.\n\nTHE BROADER IMPACT\n\nDavid Horowitz became one of the leading advocates for requiring orange safety markings on toy firearms after the incident. He later appeared before the U.S. Senate with a table of real and replica weapons, asking legislators whether they genuinely believed a police officer could distinguish between them in a split second. This advocacy contributed to federal legislation requiring bright orange tips on toy guns sold in the United States.\n\nThe media coverage of the incident was extensive — the drama of a gunman on live television, Horowitz''s composure, the revelation that the weapon was a toy, the family connection. But as Howard Rosenberg observed in the Los Angeles Times, the content of what Stollman actually alleged was largely treated as "rambling" and "befuddling" rather than examined on its merits. The story became about the gun and the bravery — not the statement.\n\nWHAT IT MEANS\n\nA man with documented mental health issues hijacked a live television broadcast to deliver specific allegations about CIA operations, government psychiatric facilities, and suppressed military intelligence — then the broadcast was killed in 28 seconds, the full recording was locked away, and the man was institutionalized. The factual questions are narrow: Why has the full seven-minute recording never been released? KNBC confirmed it exists. The Los Angeles Times confirmed the cameras continued recording. The Lost Media Wiki classifies it as unreleased. Nearly four decades later, the footage remains sealed.\n\nThe claims Stollman made — about CIA psychological programs, government surveillance of computer users, suppressed UFO files, and covert biological weapons research — were dismissed as the ravings of a mentally ill man in 1987. Several of those topics have since entered mainstream public discourse: the CIA''s MK-Ultra program was confirmed through declassified documents and congressional hearings; NSA mass surveillance of digital communications was exposed by Edward Snowden in 2013; and the U.S. government held its first public congressional hearings on UAP/UFO phenomena in 2022 after decades of denial.\n\nNone of this validates Stollman''s specific claims about cloning or alien forces. But it raises a documented question: a television station recorded a full statement that it has never allowed the public to see, and the only official explanation for why — given nearly 40 years ago — was a "change in priorities" for reporting the story. The footage exists. It has not been released.\n\nMLA CITATIONS:\n\nRohrlich, Ted, and Ted Thackrey Jr. "Intruder With Toy Gun Puts KNBC off Air." Los Angeles Times, 20 Aug. 1987.\nhttps://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1987-08-20-mn-3662-story.html\n\n"Man Pulls Gun on KNBC''s Horowitz During Newscast." Los Angeles Times, 20 Aug. 1987.\nhttps://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1987-08-20-mn-3655-story.html\n\nRosenberg, Howard. "TV as Hostage: Now What Is the Message?" Los Angeles Times, 21 Aug. 1987.\nhttps://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1987-08-21-ca-2406-story.html\n\nPristin, Terry. "3 Years'' Probation in Toy Gun Case." Los Angeles Times, 8 Jun. 1988.\nhttps://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1988-06-08-me-4034-story.html\n\n"Felony Trial Ordered in Newscast Takeover." United Press International, 4 Sep. 1987.\nhttps://www.upi.com/Archives/1987/09/04/Felony-trial-ordered-in-newscast-takeover/6371557726400/\n\n"KNBC Channel 4 News (Partially Found Hostage-Taking Footage of Television Consumer Reporter; 1987)." Lost Media Wiki.\nhttps://lostmediawiki.com/KNBC_Channel_4_News_(partially_found_hostage-taking_footage_of_television_consumer_reporter;_1987)\n\n"DARPA LifeLog." Wikipedia.\nhttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DARPA_LifeLog\n\n"KNBC Studio Gunman 1987." YouTube, uploaded 20 May 2024.\nhttps://www.youtube.com/watch?v=STDQnab8DbQ',
  'https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1987-08-20-mn-3662-story.html',
